	abstract = {Calmer, a robotic device that simulates key pain-reducing components of skin-to-skin contact, including heart beat sounds, breathing motion, and touch, was developed to augment clinical pain management. Forty-nine preterm infants were randomized to facilitated tucking or Calmer treatment. Heart rate and heart rate variability were continuously recorded from a single-lead surface ECG sampled at 1000 Hz and processed using Mindware. No significant differences were found between groups on any outcome measures.},
